f:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Hyperliquid calculates funding rates every hour using the premium/discount between the perpetual price and ADA spot price, with payments occurring at the top of each hour. The on-chain order book ensures transparent price discovery without relying on external oracles for the funding rate calculation. Traders pay or receive funding based on their position side and the rate direction, with long positions paying when rates are positive and shorts paying when negative. The 1-hour frequency creates more granular arbitrage opportunities compared to the standard 8-hour intervals on most centralized exchanges."}]
10:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ADA","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ADA represents one of the most liquid L1 tokens on Hyperliquid, making it suitable for funding rate arbitrage strategies that require tight spreads and sufficient depth. The token's consistent trading activity and established DeFi presence create regular funding rate imbalances, particularly during Cardano ecosystem developments or broader altcoin momentum. ADA's correlation patterns with Bitcoin and Ethereum often create predictable funding rate divergences that sophisticated traders can exploit."}]]}]
11:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical ADA Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ADA funding rates on Hyperliquid typically range from -0.05% to +0.15% per hour during normal market conditions, with spikes reaching ±0.5% during high volatility periods. The 1-hour intervals create more frequent rate resets compared to traditional 8-hour cycles, leading to smaller but more consistent arbitrage opportunities. Historical data shows ADA funding rates tend to turn negative during broader crypto selloffs as DeFi traders hedge their spot positions, while ecosystem-specific news often drives prolonged positive funding periods. The on-chain nature of Hyperliquid means funding rates react more quickly to DeFi market sentiment compared to centralized exchanges focused on traditional derivatives trading."}]]}]
12:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Cross-Exchange Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ADA funding rates on Hyperliquid frequently diverge from centralized exchanges like Binance and Bybit, creating cross-platform arbitrage opportunities for traders with positions on multiple venues. The 1-hour funding frequency allows for more precise timing of arbitrage entries and exits compared to 8-hour cycles elsewhere. DeFi-native traders on Hyperliquid often exhibit different positioning patterns than CEX users, leading to sustained rate differentials during market trends. Successful arbitrage requires monitoring rate convergence patterns and understanding how Cardano-specific events affect funding differently across DEX versus CEX platforms."}]]}]
13:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Funding rate arbitrage on Hyperliquid carries unique risks including potential smart contract vulnerabilities, single-chain dependency, and USDC-only settlement which creates additional stablecoin exposure. The newer platform's limited track record means less historical data for modeling extreme funding rate scenarios compared to established centralized exchanges. Traders must account for potential slippage during volatile periods when the on-chain order book may have wider spreads than expected. The 1-hour funding frequency requires active monitoring and may result in more frequent transaction costs, particularly for smaller position sizes where gas fees could erode arbitrage profits."}]]}]
14:["$","$L16",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often are ADA funding rates calculated on Hyperliquid?","answer":"ADA funding rates on Hyperliquid are calculated and paid every hour at the top of the hour. This is more frequent than most centralized exchanges which use 8-hour intervals, creating unique arbitrage timing opportunities."},{"question":"Can I arbitrage ADA funding rates between Hyperliquid and centralized exchanges?","answer":"Yes, cross-exchange funding rate arbitrage is possible by taking opposite positions on Hyperliquid and centralized exchanges. The 1-hour versus 8-hour funding frequency difference creates additional complexity but also more opportunities for profit."},{"question":"What are the main risks of ADA perpetual trading on Hyperliquid?","answer":"Key risks include smart contract risk from the newer protocol, single L1 dependency, USDC settlement exposure, and potentially wider spreads during volatile periods. The platform's limited operating history also means less stress-tested risk management systems."},{"question":"How does Hyperliquid's on-chain order book affect ADA funding rates?","answer":"The fully on-chain order book provides transparent price discovery for funding rate calculations without external oracle dependencies. This can lead to faster funding rate adjustments compared to exchanges using off-chain matching engines with oracle-based pricing."}]}]
